## Results

| Split | Direction | Pairwise Rank | Best Asset | Correlation | MAE | RMSE |
| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| train `[0,730)` | 0.487915 | 0.505747 | 0.352924 | -0.000884998 | 0.0219201 | 0.0277276 |
| eval `[760,1088)` | 0.504065 | 0.519309 | 0.381098 | -0.000355394 | 0.0219391 | 0.0277446 |

Auxiliary terms stayed effectively random:

```text
train.mean_edge_return_auxiliary_loss = 1.13708
train.mean_edge_return_auxiliary_direction_loss = 0.693607
train.mean_edge_return_auxiliary_rank_loss = 0.693156

eval.mean_edge_return_auxiliary_loss = 1.13736
eval.mean_edge_return_auxiliary_direction_loss = 0.693148
eval.mean_edge_return_auxiliary_rank_loss = 0.693147
```

The `0.693...` direction/rank values are essentially `log(2)`, which means the
binary sign/rank terms did not learn useful separation.

## Comparison

Prior edge projection from the old MDN was already near random:

```text
old_mdn.eval.directional_accuracy = 0.507453
old_mdn.eval.pairwise_rank_accuracy = 0.491531
old_mdn.eval.best_asset_agreement = 0.295732
old_mdn.eval.correlation = 0.00355936
```

The frozen-representation supervised edge probe was materially better:

```text
frozen_representation.eval.directional_accuracy = 0.738482384824
frozen_representation.eval.pairwise_rank_accuracy = 0.707994579946
frozen_representation.eval.best_asset_agreement = 0.597560975610
frozen_representation.eval.correlation = 0.622333108679
```

So the representation appears to expose some edge signal, but this MDN readout
and objective still do not convert it into tradable edge forecasts.

## Interpretation

The result narrows the failure:

```text
Not proven:
  representation has no signal.

Now shown:
  a light edge auxiliary term on the MDN node-potential expected value is not
  sufficient to recover edge direction/rank.
```

The next likely fix is not PPO tuning. It is a stronger forecast-side change:

```text
synthetic_mdn_direct_edge_readout.v1
```

That milestone should test a dedicated edge-return readout/head, or an
edge-space forecast head, where edge return is a first-class supervised output
instead of only an auxiliary projection of node potentials.
